First, let's recall that the **Earnings per Share** $(\operatorname{EPS})$ can be calculated by the following formula:

$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{EPS}=\frac{\text{Net Income}-\text{Preferred Dividens}}{\text{Common Shares Outstanding}}
\end{equation}
$$

Now, from the exercise we know that:

<center>

| Concept|Bread |Butter |
|:--:|:--:|:--:|
|Earnings |$\$230,000$ |$\$690,000$ |
|Shares Outstanding |$73,000$ |$146,000$ |
|Price-earnings ratio|$6.35$|$12.7$|
<center>Table 1: The Givens.<br><br>

So, the **Net Income** after the merger can be calculated by adding the given **Earnings** of both Firms:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Net Income}&=\text{Earnings }_{\text{Butter}}+\text{Earnings }_{\text{Bread}}\\
&=\$690,000+\$230,000\\
&=\$920,000
\end{align*}
$$

Now, the **Common Shares Outstanding** after the merger is the sum of the Butter shares and the received shares from Bread:


$$
\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Common}\\ 
\text{Shares}\\
\text {Outstanding}
\end{array}
&=\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares}\\
\text {Outstanding}
\end{array}_{\text{Butter}}+\left(\begin{array}{c}
\text{Shares}\\
\text {Outstanding}
\end{array}_{\text{Bread}}\times \begin{array}{c}
\text{Received}\\
\text {Shares ratio}
\end{array}\right)\\[20pt]

&=146,000+\left(73,000\times\frac{1}{3}^{~*}\right)\\[10pt]

&=170,333^{~**}
\end{align*}
$$

\* *The received shares ratio is part of the given information; one of three shares of Bread is held after the merge.*

\** *The result has been truncated.*

Now, there is no information of **Preferred Dividends** in the firms, so ***<span style="color: #C34632">let's assume that there are no preferred dividends</span>***. 

Now we are ready to calculate the **Earnings per Share** after the merge by solving the resulting equation $(1)$ we have by evaluating the previous partial results:

$$
\begin{align*}
\operatorname{EPS}&=\frac{\text{Net Income}-\text{Preferred Dividens}}{\text{Common Shares Outstanding}}\\[10pt]
&=\frac{\$920,000-0}{170,333}\\[10pt]
&=\boxed{\$5.4012}
\end{align*}
$$

So, this profitability ratio shows us the amount of money that the Firms merger will bring.

Now, the **Price-earnings ratio** $(\operatorname{PE})$ can be determined by the following formula:

$$
\begin{equation}
\operatorname{PE}=\frac{\text{Price per Share}}{\text{Earnings per share}_{\text{After Merge}}}
\end{equation}
$$

Where 

$$\text{Price per Share}=\frac{\text{Earnings} \times\operatorname{EPS}}{\text{Shares outstanding}}$$

and the value of the Earnings per share was previously calculated:
$$\operatorname{EPS}_{\text{After Merge}}=5.4012$$

Now, let's evaluate the previous results into formula $(3)$ and find the synergy:

$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Synergy}&=\text{Cost to the firm Butter of the acquisition}-V_B\\[10pt]
&=\$1,251,859.97-\$1,460,500\\[10pt]
&=\textcolor{#C34632}{(\$208,640.033)}
\end{align*}
$$
